{"componentChunkName":"component---src-templates-chapter-level-2-chapter-level-2-tsx","path":"/topics/syphilis/background-information/prognosis/","result":{"pageContext":{"chapter":{"id":"b748bc0a-b4dd-5cd5-a38c-5a8565c1a29a","slug":"prognosis","fullItemName":"Prognosis","depth":2,"htmlHeader":"<!-- begin field 35c43362-4e0e-4c0a-9acf-ab25011f1ea7 --><h2>What is the prognosis?</h2><!-- end field 35c43362-4e0e-4c0a-9acf-ab25011f1ea7 -->","summary":"","htmlStringContent":"<!-- begin item b4a2cf14-06bf-4afd-88fe-ab25011f1e6a --><!-- begin field 556ec3d4-184a-4c1d-9e40-ab25011f1ea7 --><ul><li>Syphilis can be cured if treated with appropriate antibiotics before <a class=\"topic-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/syphilis/background-information/complications/\">complications</a> develop.</li><li>Untreated, around a third of cases progress to later stages of disease which can result in severe, sometimes irreversible, cardiovascular, neurological and ocular <a class=\"topic-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/syphilis/background-information/complications/\">complications</a>. </li><li>Treatment in late syphilis usually halts infection but some <em>Treponema</em> spirochetes can persist in protected sites such as the eye and central nervous system.<ul><li>Cardiovascular and neurological lesions that develop as a result of syphilis may continue to progress despite treatment.</li><li><a class=\"topic-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/syphilis/diagnosis/when-to-suspect-syphilis/#tertiary-syphilis\">Gummatous lesions</a> resolve rapidly with appropriate syphilis treatment.</li></ul></li><li>People with HIV who are co-infected with syphilis may be at increased risk of neurologic complications.</li></ul><p>[<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/syphilis/references/\">Clement, 2014</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/syphilis/references/\">CDC, 2015a</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/syphilis/references/\">Kinghorn, 2016</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/syphilis/references/\">WHO, 2016</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/syphilis/references/\">Peeling, 2017</a>]  [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/syphilis/references/\">BHIVA, 2018</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/syphilis/references/\">BMJ Best Practice, 2019</a>]</p><!-- end field 556ec3d4-184a-4c1d-9e40-ab25011f1ea7 --><!-- end item b4a2cf14-06bf-4afd-88fe-ab25011f1e6a -->","topic":{"id":"e20bf9b2-b7e3-5fd7-8829-79eff4ba17c6","topicId":"acdacd5c-088e-4bc3-b3f7-ec4a5cdf69d3","topicName":"Syphilis","slug":"syphilis","lastRevised":"Last revised in December 2019","chapters":[{"id":"e937b36a-5802-56e1-8c33-d31a18aa8993","fullItemName":"Summary","slug":"summary","subChapters":[]},{"id":"8e1009a7-fe76-55c5-a3b4-71f4ab22bd6e","fullItemName":"Have I got the right topic?","slug":"have-i-got-the-right-topic","subChapters":[]},{"id":"3744efb5-ed9a-556d-b9ca-9497279f7760","fullItemName":"How up-to-date is this topic?","slug":"how-up-to-date-is-this-topic","subChapters":[{"id":"1a6d6164-e61e-5a2b-899c-b42fdd49c070","slug":"changes","fullItemName":"Changes"},{"id":"42b3bae7-13c9-5f24-8610-e6373d51db6c","slug":"update","fullItemName":"Update"}]},{"id":"783939a0-7dd0-51dc-b0f1-1a79adaeeca2","fullItemName":"Goals and outcome measures","slug":"goals-outcome-measures","subChapters":[{"id":"481c647b-0185-5ec1-944f-ea3f095a698e","slug":"goals","fullItemName":"Goals"},{"id":"5d1c604c-5520-5fd3-906b-277d5bc648e4","slug":"outcome-measures","fullItemName":"Outcome measures"},{"id":"c1d0b67c-29a5-571e-a1e8-8037aa0cca4c","slug":"audit-criteria","fullItemName":"Audit criteria"},{"id":"7c0ed1af-9d86-5a85-a39d-bac1f3ee5aa6","slug":"qof-indicators","fullItemName":"QOF indicators"},{"id":"b5682ffb-43d2-5180-b6ef-2442bbeddb7